Given its role in metabolic function, some have proposed that UCP1 could be one of the many hundreds of genes hypothesized to be implicated in common obesity phenotypes; indeed, some variants have been shown to be related to obesity.

    1. Traits like common obesity, in which tens to hundreds of genes contribute incrementally small amounts of variation to the distribution of the phenotype, are called what? (2 points)
      1. Monogenic
      1. Oligogenic
      1. Polygenic
      1. Discrete


    1. Such complex traits often follow a normal distribution. Which of the following are characteristics of the normal distribution? (2 points)
      1. Trait values are distributed symmetrically about the mean
      1. The variance in trait values is the average of the squared difference of each value from the mean
      1. About 68% of the sample is within 1 standard deviation from the mean
      1. It shows high levels of skew

      1. Gregor Mendel
      1. Sir Francis Galton
      1. Charles Darwin
      1. Leslea Hlusko

Despite its unique role in thermogenesis, UCP1 is not an entirely unique gene. There are actually multiple mitochondrial uncoupling proteins found in the human genome. For the purposes of this exam, we’ll focus on a paralog of UCP1 called UCP3, which has also been implicated in thermoregulatory adaptations in humans.

    1. UCP1 has no splice variants, meaning that the coding region of the gene can only be transcribed to make one functional protein. Scroll down to the interactive map for UCP3. A Relict Population in Xishuangbanna

Imagine you meet a relict population descended from the Chinese Dai of Xishuangbanna, China, found isolated for generations high in the mountains. When you genotype this population (n = 250), you observe the following genotype counts for rs145884716:

  • GG = 115

  • GA = 18

  • GT = 76

  • TT = 24

  • TA = 10

  • AA = 7

    1. What is the frequency of the ‘A’ allele in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. What is the frequency of the ‘G’ allele in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. If this SNP is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, what is the expected count of ‘AA’ genotyped individuals in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. If this SNP is in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium, what is the expected count of ‘GT’ genotyped individuals in this population? (0.5 points)

    1. What is the Chi-squared value of the observed genotype counts vs. the genotype counts expected under Hardy-Weinberg Equilibrium? (2 points)

    1. What are the degrees of freedom for this test? (1 points)




    1. Using the above table to estimate the P-value of this test, it this SNP in Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium in this relict population? (2 points)

    1. Under the Modern Synthesis definition of evolution, has this relict population evolved since it first split from the Chinese Dai of Xishuangbanna, China? (2 points)


    1. Look again at the Ensembl page for this particular UCP3 variant (rs145884716). What kind of consequence does the minor allele code for? What does this mean for the phenotype of those that possess the minor allele? (2 points)
